ection. </gallery> === Human-Shaped Haniwa === Human-shaped haniwa were placed in outlying sections of Kofuns, including depictions of leaders, shamans, musicians, warriors, and common folk. These representations provide insight into costumes, social hierarchies, and ceremonial roles. <gallery> еӨӘз”°еёӮйЈҜеЎҡз”әеҮәеңҹ еҹҙијӘ жҢӮз”ІгҒ®жӯҰдәә-2.JPG|[[National Treasure]]: {{ill|Haniwa Warrior in Keiko Armor|ja|еҹҙијӘ жҢӮз”ІжӯҰдәә|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniwa Warrior in Keiko Armor|qq=}} (excavated from {{ill|Iizuka, Ota City|ja|еӨӘз”°еёӮйЈҜеЎҡз”ә|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iizuka, Ota City|qq=}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|зҫӨйҰ¬зңҢ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunma Prefecture|qq=}}) - Tokyo National Museum collection. </gallery> === Animal-Shaped Haniwa === Animal-shaped haniwa, especially horses, emphasized the authority of the deceased. Other animals such as {{ill|dogs|ja|зҠ¬|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/dogs|qq=}}, {{ill|birds|ja|йөң|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/birds|qq=}}, and {{ill|boars|ja|гӮӨгғҺгӮ·гӮ·|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/boars|qq=}} are also represented, reflecting the human-animal relationships of the time. <gallery> еҹјзҺүзңҢзҶҠи°·еёӮдёҠдёӯжқЎж—Ҙеҗ‘еі¶еҮәеңҹ еҹҙијӘ йҰ¬-2.JPG|Horse-shaped haniwa (excavated from {{ill|Kumagaya City|ja|зҶҠи°·еёӮ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumagaya City|qq=}}, {{ill|Saitama Prefecture|ja|еҹјзҺүзңҢ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefecture|qq=}}) - Tokyo National Museum collection. </gallery> == Related Research == Research on figurative haniwa has evolved since the early 20th century. In 1931, Morikazu Goto's work introduced interpretations linking these haniwa to funerary ceremonies {{Sfn|Goto|1931|pp=26-50}}. Subsequent excavations, such as those at {{ill|Shibayama Kofun Cluster|ja|иҠқеұұеҸӨеўізҫӨ|1=Shibayama Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibayama Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibayama Kofun Cluster|qq=}} in Chiba Prefecture, revealed detailed haniwa arrangements, contributing to an understanding of their ceremonial contexts {{Sfn|Otsuka et al.|1989|p=487}}. == Changes Over Time == The evolution of figurative haniwa can be divided into four stages: # '''Stage 1''': Early 4th century - Initial use of house-shaped haniwa at mound summits. # '''Stage 2''': Late 4th century - Introduction of haniwa groupings on mounded terraces. # '''Stage 3''': Mid-5th to mid-6th century - Appearance of more diverse figures and ritual arrangements. # '''Stage 4''': Late 6th century - Simplification and reduction in types of figurative haniwa. == Notes == {{Reflist|group="жіЁ"}} == References == {{Reflist|30em}} == See Also == * {{ill|Haniwa|ja|еҹҙијӘ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haniwa|qq=}} * {{ill|Cylindrical haniwa|ja|еҶҶзӯ’еҹҙијӘ|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical haniwa|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=}} * {{ill|Shibayama Kofuns and Haniwa Museum|ja|иҠқеұұеҸӨеўігғ»гҒҜгҒ«гӮҸеҚҡзү©йӨЁ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibayama Kofuns and Haniwa Museum|qq=}} {{Japanese-history-stub}}
