G|House with figures (excavated from [[:en:Saitobaru Kofun Cluster|Saitobaru Kofun Cluster]], [[:en:Miyazaki Prefecture|Miyazaki Prefecture]], [[:en:Saito, Miyazaki|Saito]]) - [[:en:Tokyo National Museum|Tokyo National Museum]] collection. </gallery> === Vessel-Shaped Haniwa === These haniwa, positioned to protect house-shaped haniwa, depict various items such as lids, ceremonial umbrellas, and insignia of prestige, including [[:en:Crown|crowns]], [[:en:Chair|chairs]], containers like {{ill|Shingu|lt=Shingu|lt=Tall stands|ja|й«ҳеқҸ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tall stands|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to зҘһе…·}} and {{ill|pots|ja|еЈә|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/pots|qq=}}, and weapons like [[:en:еӨ§еҲҖ|swords]], bows, and armor. These objects are crucial for reconstructing funerary rituals. <gallery> е®қеЎҡ1еҸ·еўіеҮәеңҹ иҲ№еҪўеҹҙијӘ (1еҸ·иҲ№).JPG|Boat-shaped haniwa (excavated from {{ill|Takarazuka Kofun (Mie)|lt=Takarazuka Kofun (Mie)|lt=Takarazuka Kofun (Matsusaka)|ja|е®қеЎҡеҸӨеўі|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takarazuka Kofun (Matsusaka)|qq=}}, [[:en:Matsusaka|Matsusaka]], [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]]) - Matsusaka City collection. </gallery> === Human-Shaped Haniwa === Human-shaped haniwa were placed in outlying sections of Kofuns, including depictions of leaders, shamans, musicians, warriors, and common folk. These representations provide insight into costumes, social hierarchies, and ceremonial roles. <gallery> еӨӘз”°еёӮйЈҜеЎҡз”әеҮәеңҹ еҹҙијӘ жҢӮз”ІгҒ®жӯҰдәә-2.JPG|[[National Treasure]]: [[:en:Haniwa Warrior in Keiko Armor|Haniwa Warrior in Keiko Armor]] (excavated from {{ill|Iizuka, Ota City|ja|еӨӘз”°еёӮйЈҜеЎҡз”ә|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iizuka, Ota City|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, [[:en:Gunma Prefecture|Gunma Prefecture]]) - Tokyo National Museum collection. </gallery> === Animal-Shaped Haniwa === Animal-shaped haniwa, especially horses, emphasized the authority of the deceased. Other animals such as