zed the authority of the deceased. Other animals such as {{ill|dogs|ja|зҠ¬|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/dogs|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to гӮӨгғҢ}}, {{ill|birds|ja|йөң|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/birds|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to гӮҰз§‘}}, and [[:en:Wild boar|boars]] are also represented, reflecting the human-animal relationships of the time. <gallery> еҹјзҺүзңҢзҶҠи°·еёӮдёҠдёӯжқЎж—Ҙеҗ‘еі¶еҮәеңҹ еҹҙијӘ йҰ¬-2.JPG|Horse-shaped haniwa (excavated from [[:en:Kumagaya|Kumagaya City]], [[:en:Saitama Prefecture|Saitama Prefecture]]) - Tokyo National Museum collection. </gallery> == Related Research == Research on figurative haniwa has evolved since the early 20th century. In 1931, Morikazu Goto's work introduced interpretations linking these haniwa to funerary ceremonies {{Sfn|Goto|1931|pp=26-50}}. Subsequent excavations, such as those at [[:en:Shibayama Kofun Cluster|Shibayama Kofun Cluster]] in Chiba Prefecture, revealed detailed haniwa arrangements, contributing to an understanding of their ceremonial contexts {{Sfn|Otsuka et al.|1989|p=487}}. == Changes Over Time == The evolution of figurative haniwa can be divided into four stages: # '''Stage 1''': Early 4th century - Initial use of house-shaped haniwa at mound summits. # '''Stage 2''': Late 4th century - Introduction of haniwa groupings on mounded terraces. # '''Stage 3''': Mid-5th to mid-6th century - Appearance of more diverse figures and ritual arrangements. # '''Stage 4''': Late 6th century - Simplification and reduction in types of figurative haniwa. == Notes == {{Reflist|group="жіЁ"}} == References == {{Reflist|30em}} == See Also == * [[:en:Haniwa|Haniwa]] * {{ill|Cylindrical haniwa|ja|еҶҶзӯ’еҹҙијӘ|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical haniwa|13=User:Immanuelle/Cylindrical Haniwa|qq=}} * [[:en:Shibayama Kofun Haniwa Museum|Shibayama Kofuns and Haniwa Museum]] {{Japanese-history-stub}}
